<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-10-10T07:25:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-10-10T07:25:00-05:00" n="554" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d554">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/1720: Telegram</note>
                                <head>
                                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Ethiopia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Engert</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                            State</gloss>
                                    </hi>
                                </head>
                                <opener>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                                        <placeName>
                                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Addis Ababa</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-10T15:00:00+02:35">October 10, 1935—3 p.m.</date>
                                        <lb/> [Received 8:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>121. Italian Minister informs me that he received this morning a
                                    note from the Ethiopian Government requesting him to make
                                    preparations for his early departure. He is accused of using his
                                    radio for transmission in violation of his promise not to do so.
                                    Vinci denies the accusation categorically and states that since
                                    October 3 he has used it only for the reception of messages
                                    about which nothing had been said.</p>
                                <p>He has just shown me his orders from Rome to depart with his
                                    personnel but without any indication as to which Legation would
                                    be requested to look after Italian interests.</p>
                                <p>Since my 112, October 5, 2 p.m., one more Italian Consul has
                                    arrived safely and without the slightest incident. Only one now
                                    remains and the Minister will endeavor to await his arrival
                                    too.</p>
                                <closer>
                                    <signed>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Engert</hi>
                                    </signed>
                                </closer>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>